import nltk
nltk.download('punkt')
nltk.download('averaged_perceptron_tagger')
nltk.download('stopwords')
nltk.download('wordnet')

# Open the file with UTF-8 encoding
with open('text.txt', 'r', encoding='utf-8') as file:
    sentence = file.read()

# Display the content to verify it's read correctly
print(sentence)

# Tokenization
tokens = nltk.word_tokenize(sentence)
print("Tokens:", tokens)

# POS Tagging
tagged = nltk.pos_tag(tokens)
print("POS Tagged Tokens:", tagged)

# Stop Word Removal
from nltk.corpus import stopwords

stop_words = set(stopwords.words('english'))
filtered_tokens = [word for word in tokens if word.lower() not in stop_words]
filtered_text = ' '.join(filtered_tokens)
print("Filtered Text (Stop Words Removed):", filtered_text)

# Stemming & Lemmatization
from nltk.stem import WordNetLemmatizer
from nltk.stem import PorterStemmer

lemmatizer = WordNetLemmatizer()
stemmer = PorterStemmer()

lemmatized_tokens = [lemmatizer.lemmatize(token) for token in filtered_tokens]
stemmed_tokens = [stemmer.stem(token) for token in filtered_tokens]
print("Lemmatized Tokens:", lemmatized_tokens)
print("Stemmed Tokens:", stemmed_tokens)

# Term Frequency and Inverse Document Frequency
tf_dict = {word: lemmatized_tokens.count(word) for word in lemmatized_tokens}

tf = {word: count / len(tf_dict) for word, count in tf_dict.items()}
print("Term Frequency (TF):", tf)

It is a disease that can affect anyone in a monumental, colossal way. It is a disease that
many people devote their lives to, either battling through it or striving for a cure. It is a disease
that can be curable, but many unfortunate souls lose their lives battling it. It is cancer.
Cancer had made a home in my father’s tonsil in the summer of 2011. Initially, we all
thought this protruding lump on the side of his neck was just a swollen gland. It began to grow
larger throughout the summer, and it started to cause pain. Daddy, being the stubborn man he
is, would not go to the doctor. In March, he finally went to the doctor for a check-up. They
gave him antibiotics. He was on the medicine for a few months. However, it failed to help. He
was then referred to an ear, nose and throat doctor, who did a needle biopsy and an X-ray that
proved negative for cancer. This doctor thought it was a congenital cyst. Numerous tests were
run, and we were told the life-changing news. “I’m sorry to inform you. You have tonsil
cancer.”
Tonsils are two oval-shaped pads in the back of the mouth that are part of the body’s
germ-fighting immune system. Tonsil cancer often causes difficulty swallowing and a sensation that something is caught in one’s throat. The doctor’s first step of action was to remove the affected tonsil. This procedure is called tonsillectomy. Undergoing such a procedure at the age of forty-nine was extremely difficult. During the surgery, Daddy’s throat collapsed. The doctors had taken the affected tonsil out, but there was still one tonsil in his
throat that needed to be removed. After his throat collapsed, the doctors medically paralyzed
Daddy to get the muscles to relax in order to intubate him. However, they would not take the
risk of getting the one tonsil he had left.
The next step of action was chemotherapy and radiation. During the treatments, I
witnessed my father lose hair, weight, muscle mass, strength, and himself. For three months,
Daddy was “chair-ridden.” He could not lay back in a bed because there was too much
pressure on his throat; therefore he had to sit up in his recliner. He lived in that chair, besides
the trips to and from the doctors. Because of the intensity of the chemo and radiation
treatments, Daddy could not eat through his throat. He had to get a feeding tube put in his
stomach. That made the food go directly into the stomach. The only thing that could go in this
feeding tube was a liquid substance. My mom, my sister, and I all took turns putting the
substance in his feeding tube eight times a day. However, during the times when we were at
school or work, Daddy had to do it. He would say he did fill his feeding tube, but he did not,
which made him lose one hundred pounds.
After they put the feeding tube in his stomach, they put a power port in his chest. He
received his chemotherapy treatments through this port. Within the same doctor visit, two life-
impacting procedures had occurred. Throughout the treatments, Daddy was in extreme pain.
The pain was caused by the cancer itself, but mostly from the radiation; the raw skin that was
around his neck burned. Because of the pain, Daddy took several amounts of pain medication, mostly Oxycontin and Morphine. Due to the pain and the medication, Daddy would be blacked out for days. The only way to try to escape the pain was to sleep.
Cancer had a chain around my family for one long year. One long year of agony.
Cancer not only pierced my dad’s life, but affected me as well. I learned at a young age that
life is not filled with rainbows and butterflies, but rather pain and suffering. Witnessing such a
devastating event for such a long period of time can make one insane. I wanted to get away
from it all. I did not want to see the strong, fearless man that I looked up to, to become so
weak. However, I had nowhere to go. Like the young girl in Annie Dillard’s autobiographical
story, “The Chase,” as she was running for her life, she felt like there was nowhere to go:
“Mikey and I had nowhere to go, in our own neighborhood or out of it.” The angry man kept
chasing her. It did not matter where she went, he would always be behind her, gaining on her.
Cancer was the angry man chasing me, gaining on me. It did not matter where I went, it would
always be with me. For one long year, it was always with me.

import nltk
from nltk.corpus import stopwords
from nltk.tokenize import word_tokenize
from nltk.stem import PorterStemmer
from nltk.stem import WordNetLemmatizer
from sklearn.feature_extraction.text import TfidfVectorizer

# Sample text document
text = """
Natural Language Processing (NLP) is a fascinating field of Artificial Intelligence.
It enables machines to understand, interpret, and generate human language.
NLP applications include sentiment analysis, translation, and summarization.
"""

# Step 1: Tokenization
tokens = word_tokenize(text)
print("Tokens:", tokens)

# Step 2: POS Tagging
pos_tags = nltk.pos_tag(tokens)
print("POS Tags:", pos_tags)

# Step 3: Stop Word Removal
stop_words = set(stopwords.words("english"))
filtered_tokens = [word for word in tokens if word.lower() not in stop_words]
print("Filtered Tokens (Stop Words Removed):", filtered_tokens)

# Step 4: Stemming
stemmer = PorterStemmer()
stemmed_tokens = [stemmer.stem(word) for word in filtered_tokens]
print("Stemmed Tokens:", stemmed_tokens)

# Step 5: Lemmatization
lemmatizer = WordNetLemmatizer()
lemmatized_tokens = [lemmatizer.lemmatize(word) for word in filtered_tokens]
print("Lemmatized Tokens:", lemmatized_tokens)

# Step 6: TF-IDF Calculation
# The TF-IDF vectorizer expects a list of documents, so we provide a single-element list containing our text
vectorizer = TfidfVectorizer(stop_words="english")
tfidf_matrix = vectorizer.fit_transform([text])

# Get feature names (words) and their TF-IDF scores
feature_names = vectorizer.get_feature_names_out()
tfidf_scores = tfidf_matrix.toarray()[0]

# Display TF-IDF scores
tfidf_dict = dict(zip(feature_names, tfidf_scores))

'''Therotical background -

Tokenization -is the process of breaking down a text into individual words or tokens. This is often the first step in natural language processing tasks

POS tagging -  involves labeling each word in a sentence with its corresponding part of speech, such as noun, verb, adjective, etc.

Stop words -are common words like 'the', 'is', 'and', etc., which often do not carry significant meaning in text analysis. 
Remove these stop words from the text to focus on the more meaningful content.


1. Tokenization
Tokenization is the process of breaking down a text document into smaller components, known as tokens. Tokens can be words, sentences, or subwords, depending on the task. In Natural Language Processing (NLP), word tokenization is often used to segment text into words, enabling the machine to process each word individually. Tokenization is essential as it forms the basis for other preprocessing steps. For instance, analyzing text at the word level allows us to understand the content, syntax, and semantics more precisely. Python’s Natural Language Toolkit (NLTK) provides a convenient method for tokenization.

2. Stop Word Removal
Stop words are common words that often do not add significant meaning to a text, such as "the," "is," "at," etc. Removing these words helps in focusing on the essential words that convey the main idea of a document. Stop word removal reduces noise in text data and often improves computational efficiency by reducing the number of words for analysis. NLTK offers a list of standard stop words for various languages, including English, making it easier to filter out these non-informative words.

3. Part-of-Speech (POS) Tagging
POS Tagging involves assigning a part-of-speech label to each token, such as noun, verb, adjective, etc. POS tags provide context to each word, which helps in understanding the structure and meaning of a sentence. For example, distinguishing between "book" (noun) and "book" (verb) is essential for accurate interpretation. POS tagging is used in applications like information extraction, named entity recognition, and text classification. In this practical, POS tags are generated using NLTK’s pos_tag function, which relies on pre-trained models to assign tags based on the context of words in a sentence.

4. Stemming
Stemming is the process of reducing words to their base or root forms. It involves chopping off suffixes to transform words into their root form. For example, "running" becomes "run," and "happily" becomes "happi." Stemming is typically rule-based and may produce non-standard root forms. The main advantage of stemming is its computational efficiency, but it may occasionally lead to inaccurate root forms. The Porter Stemmer, a widely used stemming algorithm in NLTK, is effective for various NLP tasks like sentiment analysis and information retrieval.

5. Lemmatization
Lemmatization is a more advanced method of reducing words to their base or dictionary forms, known as "lemmas." Unlike stemming, lemmatization considers the part of speech of the word and uses linguistic rules to derive the correct base form. For instance, "running" is converted to "run," but "better" is converted to "good" (its lemma) rather than being left unchanged. Lemmatization provides more accurate root words, which is essential in contexts where meaning must be preserved. NLTK's WordNet Lemmatizer utilizes a lexical database called WordNet to find the correct base form, making it particularly useful for tasks like text summarization and machine translation.

6. Term Frequency-Inverse Document Frequency (TF-IDF)
TF-IDF is a numerical statistic used to reflect the importance of a word in a document relative to a collection of documents (or corpus). It’s a key technique in information retrieval and text mining. TF-IDF consists of two components:

Term Frequency (TF): Measures the frequency of a term within a document. It is calculated by dividing the count of the term by the total number of terms in the document.
Inverse Document Frequency (IDF): Measures the significance of a term across multiple documents. If a word appears frequently across multiple documents, it is likely not unique or informative. IDF is calculated as the logarithm of the ratio of the total number of documents to the number of documents containing the term.
The TF-IDF score for a word is computed as the product of its TF and IDF scores, which highlights words that are unique and significant to a document within the corpus. TF-IDF is widely used in search engines, document clustering, and topic modeling.

import re
from collections import defaultdict
from nltk.corpus import stopwords
from nltk.stem import PorterStemmer
import nltk

# Download NLTK data files (run this once)
nltk.download('stopwords')

class InvertedIndex:
    def __init__(self):
        self.index = defaultdict(list)
        self.documents = []
        self.stop_words = set(stopwords.words('english'))
        self.stemmer = PorterStemmer()

    def add_document(self, doc):
        doc_id = len(self.documents)
        self.documents.append(doc)
        tokens = self.tokenize(doc)
        for token in tokens:
            if doc_id not in self.index[token]:
                self.index[token].append(doc_id)

    def tokenize(self, text):
        # Lowercase and split into words
        text = text.lower()
        tokens = re.findall(r'\b\w+\b', text)
        # Remove stop words and stem the tokens
        tokens = [self.stemmer.stem(token) for token in tokens if token not in self.stop_words]
        return tokens

    def search(self, query):
        tokens = self.tokenize(query)
        if not tokens:
            return []

        result_sets = []
        for token in tokens:
            result_sets.append(set(self.index.get(token, [])))

        if not result_sets:
            return []

        results = set.intersection(*result_sets)
        return [self.documents[doc_id] for doc_id in results]

# Example usage
documents = [
    "The quick brown fox jumps over the lazy dog",
    "The quick brown fox",
    "The brown dog is lazy",
    "Quick brown foxes are quick and brown",
]

inverted_index = InvertedIndex()

for doc in documents:
    inverted_index.add_document(doc)

# Searching for documents containing the words "quick" and "brown"
results = inverted_index.search("quick brown")
print("Search results for 'quick brown':")
for result in results:
    print(result)

# Searching for documents containing the words "lazy dog"
results = inverted_index.search("lazy dog")
print("\nSearch results for 'lazy dog':")
for result in results:
    print(result)

import nltk
from nltk.corpus import stopwords
from nltk.tokenize import word_tokenize
from collections import defaultdict

nltk.download('stopwords')
nltk.download('punkt')

# Sample documents to index
documents = {
    1: "Data science is an interdisciplinary field that uses various methods and algorithms.",
    2: "Machine learning is a branch of artificial intelligence focused on building systems that learn from data.",
    3: "Natural language processing allows computers to understand human language.",
    4: "Deep learning is a subset of machine learning dealing with neural networks."
}

# Preprocess text: Tokenize, remove stop words, and build inverted index
stop_words = set(stopwords.words("english"))
inverted_index = defaultdict(list)

# Building the inverted index
for doc_id, content in documents.items():
    # Tokenize and filter out stop words
    tokens = word_tokenize(content.lower())
    filtered_tokens = [token for token in tokens if token.isalnum() and token not in stop_words]
    
    # Populate the inverted index
    for token in filtered_tokens:
        if doc_id not in inverted_index[token]:
            inverted_index[token].append(doc_id)

# Display the inverted index
print("Inverted Index:")
for term, doc_list in inverted_index.items():
    print(f"{term}: {doc_list}")

# Document Retrieval Function
def retrieve_documents(query, inverted_index):
    # Tokenize and filter the query terms
    query_tokens = word_tokenize(query.lower())
    query_tokens = [token for token in query_tokens if token.isalnum() and token not in stop_words]
    
    # Retrieve documents containing all query terms
    result_docs = set()
    for i, token in enumerate(query_tokens):
        if token in inverted_index:
            if i == 0:
                result_docs = set(inverted_index[token])
            else:
                result_docs &= set(inverted_index[token])  # Intersection for AND query
        else:
            # If a token is not found, result will be empty (no docs contain all terms)
            result_docs = set()
            break
    
    return list(result_docs)

# Test document retrieval
query = "machine learning"
retrieved_docs = retrieve_documents(query, inverted_index)
print(f"\nDocuments matching the query '{query}': {retrieved_docs}")

# Display content of retrieved documents
for doc_id in retrieved_docs:
    print(f"Document {doc_id}: {documents[doc_id]}")

''' 
Theortical Background - 

heoretical Background: Document Retrieval Using Inverted Index
Document retrieval is a core task in Information Retrieval (IR) systems, such as search engines. One of the most efficient methods to retrieve documents based on textual queries is through the use of an inverted index. This technique is fundamental in managing and searching large text corpora and is highly optimized for fast retrieval.

1. Document Retrieval in Information Retrieval Systems
In document retrieval, the goal is to find relevant documents that contain specific terms or phrases from a user's query. The primary steps include:

Text Preprocessing: Transforming raw text data into a structured format, often involving tokenization, stop word removal, stemming, or lemmatization.
Indexing: Building a data structure to allow quick access to documents containing specific terms.
Query Processing: Interpreting a user query to retrieve relevant documents.
Ranking: Ordering retrieved documents by relevance to the query, based on various algorithms.
Inverted indexing is crucial in the indexing and query processing steps, providing an efficient way to search through large volumes of text data.

2. Inverted Index Structure
An inverted index is a data structure that maps each term in a collection of documents to a list of documents (and optionally positions within documents) where the term appears. This structure is essentially a lookup table, where:

Each unique term in the corpus serves as a key.
The value associated with each key is a list of document identifiers (IDs) that contain the term.
Example Structure of an Inverted Index:
For a collection of documents:

Document 1: "Data science is interdisciplinary."
Document 2: "Machine learning is part of artificial intelligence."

Ex Inverted Index looks like- 

{
    "data": [1],
    "science": [1],
    "interdisciplinary": [1],
    "machine": [2],
    "learning": [2],
    "artificial": [2],
    "intelligence": [2],
    ...
}

from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score, classification_report, confusion_matrix
from nltk.corpus import stopwords
import string

# Download necessary NLTK data
nltk.download('stopwords')
nltk.download('punkt')

# Load dataset (replace 'emails.csv' with the actual file path if needed)
# Assume the dataset is in CSV format with 'email' and 'label' columns.
data = pd.read_csv('email_classification1.csv')

# Preview the data
print(data.head())

# Preprocessing function
def preprocess_text(text):
    # Lowercase the text
    text = text.lower()
    # Remove punctuation
    text = text.translate(str.maketrans('', '', string.punctuation))
    # Tokenize text
    tokens = nltk.word_tokenize(text)
    # Remove stop words
    tokens = [word for word in tokens if word not in stopwords.words('english')]
    # Join tokens back to a single string
    return ' '.join(tokens)

classifier = MultinomialNB()
classifier.fit(X_train_tfidf, y_train)

# Predict on test data
y_pred = classifier.predict(X_test_tfidf)

# Evaluate the model
accuracy = accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred)
print(f"Accuracy: {accuracy:.2f}")
print("\nClassification Report:\n", classification_report(y_test, y_pred))
print("\nConfusion Matrix:\n", confusion_matrix(y_test, y_pred))

# Make sure to replace 'your_dataset.csv' with the actual path to your dataset

import pandas as pd
from sklearn.feature_extraction.text import TfidfVectorizer
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
from sklearn.svm import SVC
from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score, classification_report
import re

data = pd.read_csv('email_classification1.csv')


print(data.head())
# Split the data into features (text) and target (spam)
X = data['email']
y = data['label']

# Convert text to numerical features using TF-IDF vectorization
vectorizer = TfidfVectorizer()
X_vectorized = vectorizer.fit_transform(X)

# Split the data into training and testing sets
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X_vectorized, y, test_size=0.2, random_state=42)

svm_classifier = SVC(kernel='linear')

# Train the SVM classifier
svm_classifier.fit(X_train, y_train)

# Make predictions on the test set
y_pred = svm_classifier.predict(X_test)

# Calculate accuracy
accuracy = accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred)

# Display classification report
class_report = classification_report(y_test, y_pred, target_names=['Not Spam', 'Spam'])

def classify_email(subject):
    cleaned_subject = re.sub(r'^Subject:\s*', '', subject)  # Remove "Subject:" prefix
    vectorized_subject = vectorizer.transform([cleaned_subject])
    prediction = svm_classifier.predict(vectorized_subject)
    if prediction[0] == 1:
        return "Spam"
    else:
        return "Not Spam"

For evaluating a spam classifier beyond the confusion matrix, several key metrics help assess model performance from different perspectives. Here are some important metrics for binary classification like spam detection:

1. Precision
Definition: Precision measures the proportion of predicted spam emails that are actually spam.
Formula: 
Precision
=
True Positives (TP)

True Positives (TP)
​
 
Interpretation: High precision means the classifier is good at minimizing false positives (i.e., it doesn’t misclassify ham emails as spam). It’s useful when you want to ensure legitimate emails aren’t marked as spam.
2. Recall (Sensitivity or True Positive Rate)
Definition: Recall measures the proportion of actual spam emails that are correctly identified as spam.
Formula: 
Recall
=
True Positives (TP)
True Positives (TP) + False Negatives (FN)
Recall= 
True Positives (TP) + False Negatives (FN)
True Positives (TP)
​
 
Interpretation: High recall indicates the classifier catches most of the actual spam. This metric is crucial in spam detection as missing a spam email (false negative) can have security or productivity implications.

Formula: 
F1 Score

2

F1 Score=2×

​

Formula: 
Specificity
=
True Negatives (TN)

FPR
=
False Positives (FP)

FNR

''' 
E-mail spam filtering is a crucial component of email systems, designed to identify and separate unwanted or harmful messages (spam) from legitimate ones (ham). This process relies on various text classification algorithms and techniques in machine learning and natural language processing (NLP). Here’s a detailed overview of the theoretical foundations behind e-mail spam filtering.

1. Understanding Spam and Ham
Spam: Unsolicited and often irrelevant messages sent in bulk, usually for advertising purposes, phishing attempts, or spreading malware.
Ham: Legitimate emails that are wanted and expected by the recipient. The goal of spam filtering is to minimize the misclassification of ham as spam.
2. Text Classification Overview
Text classification is a supervised learning problem where the goal is to assign predefined labels (classes) to given text inputs based on their content. In the context of spam filtering, the classes are typically "spam" and "ham."

3. Features in Text Classification
Textual Features: Textual features are derived from the email content. Commonly used features include:
Word Frequencies: Count of how often each word appears in the email.
Term Frequency-Inverse Document Frequency (TF-IDF): A statistical measure that evaluates the importance of a word in a document relative to a collection of documents (corpus).
Presence of Specific Keywords: Certain words or phrases often indicate spam (e.g., "free," "win," "urgent").
Length of the Email: Spam emails might have unusually long or short content.
HTML and Link Analysis: Spam emails often contain more HTML formatting or external links.
4. Machine Learning Algorithms for Spam Filtering
Various machine learning algorithms can be employed for spam classification, including:

Naive Bayes Classifier: A probabilistic classifier based on Bayes' theorem, assuming independence among features. It is particularly effective for text classification tasks due to its simplicity and efficiency.
Support Vector Machines (SVM): A powerful classification technique that finds the optimal hyperplane to separate classes in a high-dimensional space.
Decision Trees: A model that splits the data into branches based on feature values, leading to a decision at each leaf node.
Random Forest: An ensemble method that combines multiple decision trees to improve classification accuracy and robustness.
Deep Learning Models: Such as recurrent neural networks (RNNs) or convolutional neural networks (CNNs), which can automatically learn features from raw text data.
5. Training and Evaluation
Training: A labeled dataset of emails is divided into training and testing sets. The classifier learns from the training set, adjusting its parameters to minimize classification errors.
Evaluation Metrics: Common metrics to evaluate the performance of spam classifiers include:
Accuracy: The proportion of correctly classified emails.
Precision: The ratio of correctly predicted spam emails to the total predicted spam emails.
Recall (Sensitivity): The ratio of correctly predicted spam emails to the actual spam emails in the dataset.
F1 Score: The harmonic mean of precision and recall, providing a balance between the two.
Confusion Matrix: A matrix that shows the true positive, true negative, false positive, and false negative counts.
6. Challenges in Spam Filtering
Evolving Spam Techniques: Spammers continuously adapt their techniques to evade filters, requiring constant updates to spam detection methods.
False Positives and Negatives: Classifying legitimate emails as spam (false positives) can lead to loss of important messages, while classifying spam as legitimate (false negatives) can expose users to threats.
Data Imbalance: Spam datasets may be imbalanced, with many more ham emails than spam. This imbalance can skew classification results, making it essential to use techniques such as oversampling, undersampling, or synthetic data generation.
7. Ensemble Methods and Hybrid Approaches
Combining multiple classifiers (ensemble methods) or integrating rule-based systems with machine learning approaches can enhance spam detection performance. For instance, some systems may use heuristics to filter obvious spam before applying a machine learning model for more nuanced classification.

Conclusion
E-mail spam filtering using text classification algorithms is a dynamic field that combines principles from machine learning, natural language processing, and information retrieval. Understanding the theoretical background behind this process is essential for developing effective spam filters that can adapt to new challenges in email communication. By leveraging appropriate algorithms and techniques, it is possible to significantly improve the accuracy and reliability of spam detection systems, protecting users from unwanted and potentially harmful messages.

import numpy as np

class PageRank:
    def __init__(self, graph, d=0.85, max_iter=100, tol=1.0e-6):
        self.graph = graph  # Dictionary of nodes and their outgoing links
        self.d = d  # Damping factor
        self.max_iter = max_iter  # Maximum number of iterations
        self.tol = tol  # Tolerance for convergence
        self.nodes = list(graph.keys())  # List of nodes
        self.num_nodes = len(self.nodes)  # Number of nodes

    def calculate_pagerank(self):
        # Initialize PageRank values
        pagerank = np.ones(self.num_nodes) / self.num_nodes

        # Create a mapping from node to its index
        node_index = {node: idx for idx, node in enumerate(self.nodes)}

        for _ in range(self.max_iter):
            new_pagerank = np.zeros(self.num_nodes)
            for node, edges in self.graph.items():
                if edges:  # Only if the node has outgoing links
                    for target in edges:
                        new_pagerank[node_index[target]] += pagerank[node_index[node]] / len(edges)

            # Apply damping factor
            new_pagerank = (1 - self.d) / self.num_nodes + self.d * new_pagerank

            # Check for convergence
            if np.linalg.norm(new_pagerank - pagerank, 1) < self.tol:
                break

            pagerank = new_pagerank

        return dict(zip(self.nodes, pagerank))

# Example graph (web pages as keys and lists of links as values)
graph = {
    'A': ['B', 'C'],
    'B': ['C'],
    'C': ['A'],
    'D': ['C', 'A'],
    'E': ['B', 'D'],
}

pagerank_calculator = PageRank(graph)
pagerank_scores = pagerank_calculator.calculate_pagerank()

# Output the PageRank scores
for page, score in pagerank_scores.items():
    print(f'Page: {page}, PageRank: {score:.4f}')

import numpy as np

def page_rank(graph, damping_factor=0.85, max_iterations=100, tol=1e-6):
    # Number of pages
    num_pages = len(graph)

    # Initialize the PageRank values
    pagerank = np.ones(num_pages) / num_pages

    for _ in range(max_iterations):
        new_pagerank = np.zeros(num_pages)
        for i in range(num_pages):
            for j in range(num_pages):
                if graph[j][i]:
                    new_pagerank[i] += pagerank[j] / sum(graph[j])

        # Apply damping factor and update PageRank
        new_pagerank = (1 - damping_factor) / num_pages + damping_factor * new_pagerank

        # Check for convergence
        if np.linalg.norm(new_pagerank - pagerank) < tol:
            return new_pagerank

        pagerank = new_pagerank

    return pagerank

'''Theortical background -

PageRank is a link analysis algorithm developed by Larry Page and Sergey Brin, the co-founders of Google, while they were students at Stanford University. It was designed to rank web pages in search engine results based on their importance and relevance. Here’s a detailed theoretical background of PageRank:

1. Concept of Link Analysis
Web Structure as a Graph: The World Wide Web can be represented as a directed graph, where each web page is a node and hyperlinks between pages are directed edges. A link from page A to page B signifies that page A endorses or points to page B.
Importance of Links: The basic premise of PageRank is that more important pages are likely to receive more links from other pages. Thus, the quantity and quality of links pointing to a page determine its importance.
2. Mathematical Foundation
Rank Definition: The PageRank of a page 
𝑃

 .

𝑃

3. Damping Factor
The damping factor 
𝑑
d accounts for the probability that a user continues clicking links. If a user gets bored or lost, there is a probability 

(1−d) that they will jump to a random page. This helps to distribute the PageRank among all pages and prevents rank scores from being concentrated on a few highly-linked pages.
4. Iterative Calculation
Initial PageRank Values: Initially, all pages are assigned an equal PageRank value, typically 

 , where 
𝑁
N is the total number of pages.
Convergence: The algorithm iteratively updates the PageRank values using the recursive formula until the values converge (i.e., the change in PageRank values falls below a certain threshold) or a maximum number of iterations is reached.
5. Handling Dangling Nodes
Pages that have no outbound links (dangling nodes) can disrupt the PageRank calculation. To handle this, the algorithm can redistribute the PageRank of dangling nodes evenly among all pages in the graph, ensuring that the rank distribution remains valid.
6. Applications Beyond Web Search
Although originally developed for ranking web pages, PageRank has been adapted for various applications, including social network analysis, citation analysis in academic papers, and recommendation systems.
7. Limitations and Improvements
Limitations: PageRank is not the sole metric for determining the relevance of a page. It can be influenced by the structure of the web graph and may not capture the full context of content relevance.
Improvements: Variations and improvements to the basic PageRank algorithm have been developed, such as Personalized PageRank, which allows for user preferences to influence the ranking, and Topic-Sensitive PageRank, which considers the context of the links.

ageRank remains a fundamental algorithm in the field of information retrieval and web search, representing an early and influential approach to determining the importance of web pages. Its principles extend beyond the web and serve as a basis for many ranking algorithms in various domains. Understanding PageRank is crucial for grasping how search engines prioritize content and the significance of link structures in determining relevance.

Theoretical Background on Agglomerative Hierarchical Clustering
Agglomerative Hierarchical Clustering (AHC) is a widely used method for cluster analysis in data mining and statistics. It is part of the hierarchical clustering family, which seeks to build a hierarchy of clusters. AHC is particularly popular due to its intuitive approach and ability to create a dendrogram, which visually represents the clustering process.

1. Definition
Agglomerative Hierarchical Clustering is a bottom-up approach to clustering. It starts with each data point as an individual cluster and iteratively merges the closest clusters until a stopping criterion is met (e.g., a specified number of clusters or a distance threshold).

2. Basic Steps of AHC
The process of Agglomerative Hierarchical Clustering can be summarized in the following steps:

Initialization: Start with each data point as its own cluster. For 
𝑛
n data points, this means there are 
𝑛
n clusters initially.

Distance Calculation: Compute the distance (or similarity) between each pair of clusters. Various distance metrics can be used, such as Euclidean, Manhattan, or Cosine distance.

Cluster Merging:

Identify the two clusters that are closest to each other based on the calculated distances.
Merge these two clusters into a single cluster.
Update Distance Matrix: After merging, update the distance matrix to reflect the distances between the new cluster and the remaining clusters.

Repeat: Continue the process of merging the closest clusters until all data points are merged into a single cluster or until a specified number of clusters is reached.

Dendrogram Construction: A dendrogram can be constructed to visualize the clustering process. The dendrogram illustrates how clusters are merged at various levels of distance, helping to determine an appropriate number of clusters by cutting the dendrogram at a specific height.

3. Linkage Criteria
The way distances between clusters are calculated is determined by the linkage criteria, which can significantly influence the clustering outcome. Common linkage methods include:

Single Linkage: The distance between two clusters is defined as the shortest distance between any two points in the clusters (also known as the minimum distance).

Complete Linkage: The distance between two clusters is defined as the longest distance between any two points in the clusters (maximum distance).

Average Linkage: The distance between two clusters is the average of all pairwise distances between points in the clusters.

Ward's Linkage: This method minimizes the total within-cluster variance. It merges clusters that result in the smallest increase in total within-cluster variance after merging.

4. Advantages of AHC
Flexibility: AHC can produce a hierarchy of clusters, allowing users to select the desired number of clusters based on their specific needs.
No Prior Assumptions: Unlike some clustering methods (like k-means), AHC does not require a predefined number of clusters, making it suitable for exploratory data analysis.
Dendrogram Visualization: The dendrogram provides an intuitive visual representation of the clustering process, helping to understand the relationships between data points.
5. Disadvantages of AHC
Scalability: AHC is computationally intensive, especially for large datasets, as it requires calculating the distance matrix, which is 

Sensitivity to Noise: AHC can be sensitive to outliers, which may lead to poor clustering performance.
Linkage Method Dependence: The choice of linkage method can significantly affect the final clustering results, leading to different interpretations of the data.
Conclusion
Agglomerative Hierarchical Clustering is a powerful clustering technique that offers an intuitive and flexible way to group data points. By building a hierarchy of clusters and visualizing the process with dendrograms, AHC facilitates the exploration of complex datasets. Understanding the underlying principles and parameters of AHC is crucial for effectively applying this algorithm to various real-world applications, such as customer segmentation, document clustering, and image analysis.

import smtplib
from email.mime.multipart import MIMEMultipart
from email.mime.text import MIMEText
import time

# Email credentials and recipient
SENDER_EMAIL = "your_email@gmail.com"
SENDER_PASSWORD = "your_password"  # Gmail app-specific password or regular password
RECEIVER_EMAIL = "receiver_email@gmail.com"

# GPIO setup
GPIO.setmode(GPIO.BCM)
IR_PIN = 17  # GPIO pin where the IR sensor's OUT pin is connected
GPIO.setup(IR_PIN, GPIO.IN)

def send_alert(subject, message):
    """Send an email alert when motion is detected."""
    try:
        msg = MIMEMultipart()
        msg['From'] = SENDER_EMAIL
        msg['To'] = RECEIVER_EMAIL
        msg['Subject'] = subject
        msg.attach(MIMEText(message, 'plain'))

        server = smtplib.SMTP('smtp.gmail.com', 587)
        server.starttls()
        server.login(SENDER_EMAIL, SENDER_PASSWORD)
        server.sendmail(SENDER_EMAIL, RECEIVER_EMAIL, msg.as_string())
        server.quit()
        print("Alert sent successfully.")
    except Exception as e:
        print("Error sending alert:", e)

def monitor_motion():
    """Monitor the IR sensor and send an alert if motion is detected."""
    print("Starting motion detection...")
    
    try:
        while True:
            # Check for motion detection
            if GPIO.input(IR_PIN):
                print("Motion detected!")
                send_alert(
                    subject="Motion Alert",
                    message="Motion has been detected in the monitored area!"
                )
                # Pause to avoid multiple alerts for a single motion
                time.sleep(5)
            else:
                print("No motion detected.")
            
            # Wait a bit before checking again
            time.sleep(1)
    except KeyboardInterrupt:
        print("Stopping motion detection.")
    finally:
        GPIO.cleanup()

monitor_motion()

''' Therotcal Background - 

Here's a theoretical background on using an IR sensor with a Raspberry Pi to send alert messages through email, specifically in the context of environmental monitoring and motion detection.

Introduction to Infrared (IR) Sensors
An Infrared (IR) sensor, specifically a Passive Infrared (PIR) sensor, is a device that detects the infrared radiation emitted by objects within its field of view. Commonly used for motion detection, PIR sensors are sensitive to changes in IR radiation, which allows them to detect movements of warm objects (like humans or animals) in a monitored area. The sensor does not emit any infrared light itself; instead, it detects infrared energy passively from the surrounding environment.

How PIR Sensors Work
A PIR sensor is made up of two main components:

Pyroelectric Sensor: This detects infrared radiation levels. When an object (such as a human) moves within the range of the sensor, it causes a sudden change in infrared levels.
Fresnel Lens: This helps concentrate the infrared signals onto the sensor, expanding its range and sensitivity.
PIR sensors output a digital signal (typically HIGH or LOW) to indicate the presence or absence of motion. When no motion is detected, the signal remains LOW. When motion is detected, the sensor briefly outputs a HIGH signal.

Integrating PIR Sensors with Raspberry Pi
The Raspberry Pi has General Purpose Input/Output (GPIO) pins, which allow it to interface with various sensors and devices. By connecting the PIR sensor’s output pin to one of the GPIO pins on the Raspberry Pi, the Pi can detect when the PIR sensor detects motion.

GPIO Mode: The Raspberry Pi's GPIO is set to input mode for the PIR sensor pin, allowing it to read signals from the sensor.
Polling for Motion: The Raspberry Pi program continuously checks for a HIGH signal from the sensor, indicating motion.
Sending Alerts with Python and SMTP
The Simple Mail Transfer Protocol (SMTP) is a protocol used to send emails. Using Python's smtplib library, we can configure the Raspberry Pi to send email alerts when motion is detected. Here’s how the process works:

SMTP Setup: Configure the SMTP server details (e.g., Gmail's SMTP server) and login credentials.
Message Construction: Using Python’s email libraries, create a structured email message, including the recipient’s email address, subject, and message body.
Sending the Alert: When motion is detected, the Python program sends the email to the specified recipient to notify them of the detected motion.
Applications of PIR-Based Alerts
This type of setup has various applications in fields where monitoring movement and sending alerts is critical:

Home Security: Detect unauthorized entry into a home or office space and send alerts to notify the owner or authorities.
Industrial Monitoring: Track movement in restricted areas to ensure that only authorized personnel are present.
Energy Management: Detect presence in specific areas to control lighting or HVAC systems.
Advantages and Limitations
Advantages:

Simple Setup: PIR sensors are inexpensive and easy to install, making them suitable for basic motion detection.
Low Power Consumption: PIR sensors consume little power as they do not emit any signal, which makes them ideal for continuous monitoring.
Real-Time Alerts: Sending alerts via email provides immediate notifications, allowing for quick responses.
Limitations:

Detection Range: PIR sensors have limited range and are affected by environmental factors like temperature changes.
False Positives: The sensor can be triggered by warm objects that are not intruders (e.g., pets).
Limited Information: A PIR sensor only detects motion and cannot identify the type of movement or the moving object.
Conclusion
Using a PIR sensor with a Raspberry Pi to send email alerts is an effective solution for basic motion detection applications. 
The setup leverages the low power consumption and simplicity of PIR sensors, along with the processing capabilities of the Raspberry Pi.
When combined with SMTP, this allows for real-time email alerts, making the system useful for applications in security, 
monitoring, and energy management.

#Arduino 


const int pirPin = 2;    // PIR sensor output pin
const int ledPin = 9;    // LED pin
const int buzPin = 3;    // Buzzer pin
int motionState = LOW;   // Initial state of motion

void setup() {
  Serial.begin(9600);            // Start serial communication
  pinMode(pirPin, INPUT);         // Set PIR sensor pin as input
  pinMode(ledPin, OUTPUT);        // Set LED pin as output
  pinMode(buzPin, OUTPUT);        // Set Buzzer pin as output
}

void loop() {
  motionState = digitalRead(pirPin);  // Read PIR sensor state

  if (motionState == HIGH) {
    digitalWrite(ledPin, HIGH);       // Turn on LED
    digitalWrite(buzPin, HIGH);       // Turn on Buzzer
    Serial.println("Motion detected!");  // Print message
    delay(100);                        // Delay to prevent flooding Serial Monitor
  } else {
    digitalWrite(ledPin, LOW);        // Turn off LED
    digitalWrite(buzPin, LOW);        // Turn off Buzzer
  }

  delay(100);                          // Small delay for stability
}

    // Void setup is run only once after each power-up or reset of the Arduino board.

'''Therotical Background - 


1. Introduction to PIR Sensors

Passive Infrared (PIR) sensors detect infrared radiation (heat) emitted by objects in their field of view. They are often used in motion detection applications, as they can sense the movement of a person or animal by detecting variations in infrared light levels.
PIR sensors are "passive" because they do not emit any energy but detect changes in infrared radiation. When a warm body like a human enters the sensor's range, it triggers an output signal.
2. PIR Sensor Working Principle

A PIR sensor contains two slots made of a pyroelectric material. These slots detect infrared radiation.
When the sensor is idle, the two slots sense the same amount of infrared energy. If a warm body passes by, it first intercepts one half of the PIR sensor, creating a positive differential change between the two halves. When the body leaves, the opposite happens, creating a negative differential change.
This change in differential signals is what triggers the PIR sensor output.
3. Interfacing PIR with Arduino or Raspberry Pi

Arduino and Raspberry Pi microcontrollers can both be used to receive the digital output from the PIR sensor. The setup typically involves connecting the sensor’s output pin to a digital pin on the microcontroller.
The microcontroller reads the sensor's output as a binary signal, where "HIGH" indicates motion detected, and "LOW" means no motion.
4. LED Control Based on PIR Input

The system design involves turning an LED on or off based on the PIR sensor’s output. When motion is detected (PIR output is HIGH), the LED will turn on. When no motion is detected (PIR output is LOW), the LED turns off.
This setup is common in security applications, where the LED or even a larger light source is used to alert of nearby motion.
5. Applications of PIR-Based Motion Detection

Security Systems: PIR sensors are widely used in security systems to detect unauthorized entry.
Automation: PIR sensors help automate lighting systems, where lights turn on only when motion is detected, saving energy.
Industrial and Home Automation: PIR sensors are also used in appliances that interact with human presence, such as automatic doors, lighting, and HVAC systems.
6. Circuit Setup

The PIR sensor is connected to the Arduino or Raspberry Pi via the output pin, and the LED is connected to another pin on the board.
In Arduino, the digitalRead() function reads the PIR sensor output, and based on the result, the digitalWrite() function controls the LED.
7. Code Execution Flow

Setup: The microcontroller initializes the PIR sensor’s pin as an input and the LED’s pin as an output.
Loop: The microcontroller continuously checks the state of the PIR sensor. If motion is detected, it turns on the LED; otherwise, it turns it off.
8. Benefits of Using Arduino or Raspberry Pi for PIR Interfacing

Arduino: Simple and cost-effective, suitable for basic motion detection projects.
Raspberry Pi: Offers more processing power, suitable for more complex applications where additional processing or communication with a server may be required.

import http.client
import urllib.parse
import time
import random

# Replace with your actual ThingSpeak API key
key = 'YOUR_API_KEY'  # API Key for your ThingSpeak channel

# Function to simulate sensor data
def get_sensor_data():
    # Simulating temperature data between 20 to 30 Celsius
    return random.uniform(20.0, 30.0)

# Loop to continuously send data to ThingSpeak
while True:
    # Get simulated sensor data (temperature)
    temperature = get_sensor_data()

    # Print the simulated temperature
    print(f"Temperature: {temperature:.2f}°C")

    # Prepare the parameters for the POST request
    params = urllib.parse.urlencode({'field1': temperature, 'key': key})
    
    # Set the header for the POST request
    headers = {
        "Content-type": "application/x-www-form-urlencoded",
        "Accept": "text/plain"
    }
    
    # Make HTTP connection to ThingSpeak API
    con = http.client.HTTPConnection("api.thingspeak.com")
    
    # Send the data to the ThingSpeak channel
    con.request("POST", "/update", params, headers)
    
    # Get the response from ThingSpeak
    response = con.getresponse()
    
    # Print status and reason for the response
    print(response.status, response.reason)
    
    # Read the response data (optional)
    data = response.read()
    
    # Close the connection
    con.close()

    # Delay the loop for 15 seconds (simulate sending data every 15 seconds)
    time.sleep(15)  # You can change this interval as needed

# Import necessary libraries
import hashlib  # For hashing to ensure data integrity
from cryptography.fernet import Fernet  # For encryption
import random  # For simulating sensor data


# Generate an encryption key
key = Fernet.generate_key()
cipher = Fernet(key)


def get_sensor_data():
    return random.uniform(50, 100)  # Random temperature between 50°C and 100°C

# Encrypt the sensor data
def encrypt_data(data, cipher):
    return cipher.encrypt(data.encode())

# Decrypt the sensor data
def decrypt_data(encrypted_data, cipher):
    return cipher.decrypt(encrypted_data).decode()

# Verify data integrity using hashing
def verify_data_integrity(data):
    return hashlib.sha256(data.encode()).hexdigest()


sensor_data = f"Temperature: {get_sensor_data():.2f}°C"
print("Original Data:", sensor_data)

# Encrypt and then decrypt the data
encrypted_data = encrypt_data(sensor_data, cipher)
print("Encrypted Data:", encrypted_data)

from cryptography.fernet import Fernet

# Generate a key and write it to a file (only done once, use an existing key in real applications)
key = Fernet.generate_key()
with open("encryption_key.key", "wb") as key_file:
    key_file.write(key)

# Load the key
def load_key():
    return open("encryption_key.key", "rb").read()

# Encrypt data
def encrypt_data(data):
    fernet = Fernet(load_key())
    encrypted = fernet.encrypt(data.encode())
    return encrypted

# Decrypt data
def decrypt_data(encrypted_data):
    fernet = Fernet(load_key())
    decrypted = fernet.decrypt(encrypted_data).decode()
    return decrypted

# Simulate sensor data
sensor_data = "Temperature: 75.2°F, Humidity: 60%"

# Encrypt the sensor data
encrypted_data = encrypt_data(sensor_data)
print("Encrypted Data:", encrypted_data)

# Decrypt the sensor data
decrypted_data = decrypt_data(encrypted_data)
print("Decrypted Data:", decrypted_data)

'''therotical Background - 

1. Security in IIoT Systems
The Industrial Internet of Things (IIoT) involves the integration of physical devices (such as sensors, machines, and controllers) with the internet to improve industrial processes. These devices often transmit sensitive data over networks, making security a critical aspect of IIoT systems. Given that IIoT devices are frequently deployed in remote or less-secure environments, data protection becomes essential to avoid cyber-attacks, unauthorized access, and tampering.

2. Encryption and Decryption in IIoT Systems
In an IIoT system, encryption is used to protect sensitive data from unauthorized access while it is transmitted between devices, over networks, or when stored in databases. Decryption is the reverse process of encryption, allowing the recipient of the encrypted data to retrieve the original information securely.

Encryption converts plain text data (like sensor readings) into an unreadable format called ciphertext, using an encryption key. The ciphertext can only be turned back into its original format using the correct decryption key.
Decryption is the reverse operation of encryption. It converts the ciphertext back into readable plain text using the corresponding decryption key.
3. Encryption Techniques
There are several encryption algorithms used in IIoT systems. The one commonly used for secure communication in IIoT systems is symmetric encryption, particularly the AES (Advanced Encryption Standard) algorithm. A key characteristic of symmetric encryption is that the same key is used for both encryption and decryption. Other encryption algorithms include RSA (asymmetric encryption) and elliptic curve cryptography (ECC), but symmetric encryption is often preferred for resource-constrained IIoT devices due to its lower computational overhead.

4. Fernet Encryption (Symmetric Encryption)
The program described in the previous response uses Fernet, a symmetric encryption method provided by the cryptography library. Fernet encryption is:

Symmetric: The same key is used for both encryption and decryption.
Authenticated: It provides both encryption and integrity verification, ensuring that the data has not been tampered with during transmission.
Secret Key: A secret key is generated and used to encrypt and decrypt the data.
Fernet Key Management: The encryption key is crucial for decrypting the data. This key must be securely stored and protected to ensure the confidentiality of the data. If the key is exposed, attackers can easily decrypt sensitive information.

5. Key Management
In IIoT systems, key management is a critical aspect of securing communications. It involves generating, storing, distributing, and rotating encryption keys securely. Some key management practices include:

Key Generation: A unique key is generated to encrypt and decrypt data.
Key Storage: The key should be securely stored in a hardware security module (HSM) or a secure key management system to prevent unauthorized access.
Key Rotation: Keys should be rotated periodically to mitigate the risk of key exposure.
6. Cloud Integration
In an IIoT system, encrypted sensor data is often transmitted to the cloud for storage or analysis. By encrypting the sensor data, the system ensures that even if an attacker gains access to the data in transit or in storage, they will not be able to read or alter it without the decryption key.

7. Use Cases in IIoT
Environmental Monitoring: Sensors measuring temperature, humidity, or pressure in remote locations can encrypt data before sending it to the cloud. This ensures that the data cannot be tampered with during transmission.
Machine Monitoring: Encrypted data from machines (e.g., operational performance data) ensures that sensitive operational details are protected from competitors or unauthorized access.
Security Systems: Surveillance and security data from IIoT devices like cameras or motion sensors can be encrypted to protect privacy and prevent unauthorized monitoring.
8. Challenges
Resource Constraints: Many IIoT devices have limited computational resources, such as processing power and memory. This can make complex encryption algorithms like RSA challenging to implement. Thus, lightweight symmetric encryption algorithms like AES or Fernet are preferred for IIoT devices.
Key Management: Ensuring secure key generation, distribution, and storage in IIoT systems can be complex, especially for large-scale deployments.
Latency: Encrypting and decrypting data takes time, which can introduce latency. This is a concern for real-time applications where data needs to be processed quickly.
9. Conclusion
Encryption and decryption are essential components of security in IIoT systems. By ensuring that sensitive sensor data is encrypted during transmission and storage, IIoT systems can maintain confidentiality and integrity. The use of symmetric encryption algorithms like Fernet, along with secure key management practices, provides a balance between security and performance for resource-constrained IIoT devices.

        'Rotational speed [rpm]', 'Torque [Nm]', 'Tool wear [min]']]
